One convenient choice is to take the denominator to be \((x-5)(x+5)\) (so that \(x=\pm5\) are the only vertical asymptotes) and the numerator to be \(A(x-2)(x+1)\) (so that the zeros are \(x=2\) and \(x=-1\)).  To force the \(y\)-intercept to be 4 we require
\[
f(0)\;=\;\frac{A\,(0-2)(0+1)}{(0-5)(0+5)}
\;=\;\frac{A\cdot(-2)\cdot1}{(-5)\cdot5}
\;=\;\frac{-2A}{-25}
\;=\;\frac{2A}{25}
\;=\;4
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
A=50.
\]
Hence one such function is
\[
\boxed{f(x)=\frac{50\,(x-2)(x+1)}{(x-5)(x+5)}\,.}
\] 
You may check \(f(2)=f(-1)=0\), vertical asymptotes at \(x=\pm5\), and \(f(0)=4\).
